President Barack Obama has proclaimed October 15, 2016, as Blind Americans Equality Day in order to recognize the contributions of blind and visually impaired Americans and promote equal opportunity for all individuals with disabilities. The proclamation highlights the Americans with Disabilities Act and the efforts made to reduce discrimination and improve employment opportunities for Americans with disabilities, including those who are blind or visually impaired. The proclamation also emphasizes the importance of providing accessible education, technologies, and resources to blind and visually impaired individuals. President Obama calls upon public officials, business and community leaders, educators, librarians, and Americans across the country to observe this day with appropriate ceremonies, activities, and programs.